## 8.7 Practical Examples of Integrated Systems

### 8.7.1 Eco-Districts

**Concept:**

```
Redevelopment
of new or existing districts ↓
Integrating
all of the above elements ↓
Model districts of "living cities"
```

**Components:**

```
1. Humus Facility (Shared by District)
2. Greening of Roofs of All
Buildings3. Greening of
Walls4. Permeable Pavement5
. Rain
Garden6. Rainwater Utilization System (Each Building)
7. Reuse
of Grey Water8. Solar Power Generation (BIPV)
9. Vertical Axis Wind Power Generation10
. Geothermal Utilization11
. Biogas Power Generation12
. Smart Grid13
. Urban agriculture (rooftop vegetable gardens, community gardens)
14. EV charging infrastructure15
. Shared bicycles
```

**Goal Achievement:**

```
CO2 emissions: 80% reduction
compared to conventional Water consumption: 50% reduction
compared to conventional Energy self-sufficiency rate:
70% or more
Green coverage rate: 50% or more
Waste: 95% or more Recycled
↓
Almost carbon neutral ↓
Realizing sustainable cities
```

### 8.7.2 Phased Deployment in Existing Cities

**Phase 1: Low-cost measures (immediate start)**

```
- Increase the planting
of street trees - Permeable pavement (introduced during road repair)
- Recommend installation of rainwater tanks (subsidy)
- Recommend roof greening (subsidy)
- Replace with LED streetlights
```

**Phase 2: Medium-cost measures (within 5 years)**

```
- Construction of mulch facilities (one location in each ward)
- Mandatory rooftops of public buildings
- Recommendation of installation of solar panels (subsidies)
- Establishment of EV charging stations
```

**Phase 3: High-cost measures (within 10 years)**

```
- Building
smart grids - Promoting
geothermal utilization - Biogas power generation facilities
- Vertical farming facilities
- Promoting greening throughout the region
```

**Phase 4: Full integration (within 20 years)**

```
- Expansion
of eco-districts - Transition
of the entire city to an environmentally friendly model - Achieving carbon neutrality
```

