9.7 Impacts on the Climate System

### 9.7.1 Mitigation of Global Warming

**Direct Effects:**

CO2 reduction and absorption
: Approximately 9.5 billion tons/year
↓
Slowing of atmospheric CO2 increase
↓
Slowing of the pace of global warming```

**Taking time lag into account:**

2025-2030
: System implementation begins
↓
2030-2040: Expansion
↓
2040-2050: Significant effects
↓
2050-2070: Temperature rise peaks
↓
2070 and beyond: Stabilization and
decline```

**prediction:**

```
[No integrated system (pessimistic scenario)]
2050: +2.5°C
2100: +7-8°C

[With integrated system (hopeful scenario)]
2040: +2.0°C (peak)
2050: +2.0°C (flat)
2070: +1.7°C (starts to decline)
2100: +1.5°C (stable)
```

### 9.7.2 Avoiding Tipping Points

**Key tipping points impact:**

```
[AMOC (Atlantic Meridional Circulation)]
Ocean Breathing System
↓
Assists ocean circulation
↓
Reduces the load on AMOC
↓
Slows down weakening
↓
Gains time to reach tipping point

[Amazon Rainforest]
Reduce urban CO2 emissions
↓ Slow
global warming
↓
Mitigating the length of the dry season
↓
Reducing forest stress
↓
Avoiding savanna transformation

[Permafrost]
Slowing global warming
↓
Suppressing Arctic temperature rise
↓
Slowing permafrost melting
↓
Suppressing methane emissions
↓
Avoiding positive feedback

[Ocean Dead Zone]
Ocean Breathing System
↓
Direct elimination
↓
Completely avoid this tipping point
````

### 9.7.3 Climate Stabilization

**Feedback Loop Control:**

```
[Current runaway loop]
Global warming → Decrease in carbon sinks → Increase in CO2 → Accelerated global warming
↓
Unstoppable

[After the introduction of the integrated system]
Global warming → Integrated system absorbs more → CO2 decreases → Global warming slows down
↓
Negative feedback (stabilization)
↓
Climate controllability is
restored```

