Appendix B: Formulas and rationale

### B.1 Calculation of CO2 fixation

B.1.1 Basic Assumptions


Effects of increased nutrients: Nutrient
concentrations at a depth of 250m:
- Nitrate: 10-50 times higher than the surface
- Phosphate: 20-100 times higher than the surface
- Silicate: 50-200 times higher than the surface

Conservative assumption:
10-fold increase in phytoplankton abundance due to increased nutrients

[Area of ​​effect]
Spread by spiral discharge:
Radius 150 m
Area: π × (150)² ≈ 70,000 m² = 0.07 km²
```

B.1.2 Photosynthetic carbon fixation

```
[Primary production]
Primary production in temperate oceans:
Approximately 100-200 gC/m²/year (surface layer)

When nutrient restrictions are lifted:
Approximately 200-300 gC/m²/year

Conservative value:
20 gC/m²/year (nutrient increase only)

[Annual carbon fixation]
Affected area: 70,000 m²
Per unit area: 20 gC/m²/year
↓
Total carbon fixation:
70,000 x 20 = 1,400,000 g = 1,400 kg = 1.4 ton carbon/year

[CO2 conversion]
Molecular weight of carbon: 12
Molecular weight of CO2: 44
Conversion factor: 44/12 ≈ 3.67
↓ Fixed
CO2 amount:
1.4 × 3.67 ≈ 5.1 ton CO2/year
↓
Approximately 5 ton CO2/year/unit (conservative)

B.1.3 Uncertainty

```
[Factors for the upside]
- Plankton increase rate more than 10 times
- The impact range is wider than expected
- Additional fixation by the food chain
↓
Possible actual amount of CO2 5-10 ton/year

[Downward factors]
- Plankton growth rate less than 10 times
- Other limiting factors (light, temperature, etc.)
- Seasonal fluctuations
↓
Worst case: 2-3 ton CO2/year

[Adopted value]
Conservative median value: 5 ton CO2/year/
unit

### B.2 Energy Balance Calculation

B.2.1 Power generation


Solar
Panel Output: 1,200 W (STC) Sunshine
Hours (Equivalent): 4 h/day
Operating Rate: 17% (4/24)
Average Output: 1,200 × 0.17 = 204 W ≈ 200 W

[Wind power]
Rated output: 400 W (total of 4 units)
Average wind speed: 3 m/s
Power coefficient: approx. 0.3 (empirical)
Average output: 400 × 0.3 = 120 W

[Tidal power]
Rated output: 200 W (total of 4 units)
Average flow velocity: 0.3 m/s
Operating rate: 70%
Average output: 200 × 0.7 = 140 W

Total average power:
200 + 120 + 140 = 460 W

Daily power generation:
460 W × 24 h = 11,040 Wh ≈ 11 kWh/
day

#### B.2.2 Consumption

```
[Control system]
Microcomputer and sensor: 30 W
Communication equipment: 20 W
↓
Total: 50 W x 24 h = 1.2 kWh/day

[Compressor]
Rated output: 5 kW
Operating time: Variable (duty cycle control)

[Other]
Lighting and backup: 30 W x 24 h = 0.7 kWh/day

[Basic consumption (excluding compressor)]
1.2 + 0.7 = 1.9 kWh/day ≈ 2 kWh/
day

#### B.2.3 Compressor operating time

```
[Surplus electricity]
Power generation: 11 kWh/day
Basic consumption: 2 kWh/day
Surplus: 9 kWh/day

[Operating time]
9 kWh / 5 kW = 1.8 hours/day

[Duty cycle]
1 hour ON, 2 hours OFF
↓
Effective: 8 hours/day (33% duty)
↓
Consumption: 8 × 5 = 40 kWh/day

[Balance]
Power generation: 11 kWh/day
Consumption: 40 kWh/day
Shortage: 29 kWh/day

[Solution]
Storage battery: 20 kWh
↓
Charge on sunny days
and discharge in bad weather
↓
Balance on average weekly

or

Increased solar panel capacity (doubled to 12 m²)
↓
Average output: 400 W
Daily power generation: approx. 20 kWh/day
↓
Operable with
ease```

### B.3 Economic Calculations

B.3.1 Manufacturing Costs (Mass Production)


Material costs: $12,000 Labor
costs: $1,500
Equipment depreciation: $1,500
Logistics costs: $500
Other: $1,000
↓
Total: $16,500/
unit

B.3.2 Carbon Credit Revenue

```
CO2 fixation: 5 ton/year/unit
Carbon price: $50/ton (assumed)
↓
Annual revenue: 5 × 50 = $250/unit

1,000 units: $250,000/year
100,000 units: $25,000,000/
year````

#### B.3.3 Payback period (simple calculation)


Cost: $16,500/unit
Annual revenue: $250/unit (carbon credits only)
Payback period: 16,500 /
250 = 66 years

[However]
If other benefits are included:
- Increase in fishery resources: $70/unit/year
- Ecosystem services: $100/unit/year
- Tourism value: $50/unit/year
↓
Total: $470/unit/year
↓
Payback period: 16,500 / 470 ≈ 35 years
↓
Recoverable within the useful life (30-40 years)
````

### B.4 Calculating the Integration Effect

#### B.4.1 CO2 reduction and absorption during global deployment

```
[Ocean Breathing System]
100,000 units × 5 ton/year = 500,000 ton/year (direct)

Restoring ocean absorption capacity:
Current ocean absorption: Approximately 10 billion tons/year
Decrease due to dead zones, etc.: Estimated 10-20%
Recovery effect: 10% improvement
↓
10 billion × 0.1 = 1 billion tons/year

Total: Approximately 1 billion tons/year

[Improving urban environments]
50% of the world's urban population: 2.25 billion people
Urban CO2 emissions: Approximately 70% of the total
↓
Target emissions: 40 billion x 0.7 x 0.5 = 14 billion tons/year

50% reduction rate: 7 billion tons/year
Absorption by urban greening: 500 million tons/year
↓
Total: 7.5 billion tons/year

[Synergy]
Interaction between the two systems: Estimated 1 billion tonnes/year

[Total]
10 + 75 + 10 = 9.5 billion tons/year
↓ Approximately 24
% of current human emissions (approximately 40 billion tons/year)

